<paragraph id="114036D02B3A510DAEA3FE713423DE4E" blockId="1.[151,533,511,537]" box="[151,533,511,537]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
<heading id="4A0881BC2B3A510DAEA3FE713423DE4E" bold="true" box="[151,533,511,537]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" reason="1">
<emphasis id="238BEAC22B3A510DAEA3FE713423DE4E" bold="true" box="[151,533,511,537]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
The 
<taxonomicName id="D6FF4D532B3A510DAEFBFE713753DE4E" box="[207,357,511,537]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Delia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cardui">
<emphasis id="238BEAC22B3A510DAEFBFE713753DE4E" bold="true" box="[207,357,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Delia cardui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="114036D02B3A510DAEA3FDC432BCDFF3" blockId="1.[151,1437,586,1972]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
The two new species described below have a ventro-basal thickening on mid tarsomere 
<quantity id="D6079B352B3A510DAAACFDC432F2DE33" box="[1176,1220,586,612]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" unit="in" value="2.0">2 in</quantity>
the male sex (
<figureCitation id="89C42A552B3A510DAB59FDC43692DEDB" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1892,1916]" captionTargetBox="[260,1331,488,1891]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[257,1331,441,1896]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Delia rimiventris, male. 1. Right mid tarsus. Arrow points at basal thickening of tarsomere 2. 2. Tergites I – VI, dorsal. 3. Tergites I – VI, left lateral. Different scales for 1 and 2 – 3." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273743/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
Fig. 
<number id="A73724F72B3A510DAEA3FDFC3692DEDB" box="[151,164,626,652]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
), a derived character used by Hennig (
<number id="A73724F72B3A510DAC5AFDFC349DDEDB" box="[622,683,626,652]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1974.0">1974</number>
a) to define a 
<taxonomicName id="D6FF4D532B3A510DAD79FDFC35D6DEDC" box="[845,992,626,651]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Delia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cardui">
<emphasis id="238BEAC22B3A510DAD79FDFC35D6DEDC" box="[845,992,626,651]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Delia cardui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. The following species described from the western Palaearctic region (see Hennig 
<number id="A73724F72B3A510DAD63FD1435A2DEE3" box="[855,916,666,692]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1974.0">1974</number>
a, b, c) share this character: 
<taxonomicName id="D6FF4D532B3A510DAAD0FD14371DDE8B" authority="Zetterstedt" authorityName="Zetterstedt" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Delia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brunnescens">
<emphasis id="238BEAC22B3A510DAAD0FD1433AADEE4" box="[1252,1436,666,691]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">D. brunnescens</emphasis>
(Zetterstedt)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="D6FF4D532B3A510DAF01FD4C342DDE8B" authority="Meigen" authorityName="Meigen" box="[309,539,706,732]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Delia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cardui">
<emphasis id="238BEAC22B3A510DAF01FD4C3795DE8C" box="[309,419,706,731]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">D. cardui</emphasis>
(Meigen)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="D6FF4D532B3A510DAC12FD4C34C1DE8B" authority="Hennig" authorityName="Hennig" box="[550,759,706,732]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Delia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crinita">
<emphasis id="238BEAC22B3A510DAC12FD4C34A1DE8C" box="[550,663,706,731]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">D. crinita</emphasis>
Hennig
